A&D Weekly: A&D Div Yed of 1.1% Trending 60Bps Below 10Yr Average

We analyze the dividend payers in our coverage and market. The current avg dividend yield in A&D is \(1.1\%\) vs. 2015- 2024 avg. of \(1.6\%\) . The decline has been driven by share px growth \(>\) DPS. Leading div yield names like LMT (3.0%) come in below T- Bills \(4.3\%\) yield (vs 1pt avg delta), but favorable defense sentiment stands by the risk premium. Other high dividend payers in our coverage include LUV (2.2%), BAH (2.1%), HON (2.0%), and GD (1.8%).

Current A&D Dividend Yield of \(1.1\%\) vs. S&P's \(1.5\%\) . Across our coverage group, the average dividend yield stands at \(1.1\%\) (of the dividend- paying cos), relative to the S&P at \(1.5\%\) today and the 2015- 2024 A&D average of \(1.6\%\) . The decline versus history is a function of 1) initial pandemic- induced dividend cuts with continued instability of the supply chain and a tilt still toward capital preservation resulting in a slower return of the dividend and 2) share price performance out of the recovery outpacing dividends. Since 2019, shares have relatively outperformed, rising at a \(10\%\) CAGR vs a slower dividend growth rate of \(8\%\) . In aggregate, the highest current yields in our coverage include LMT (3.0%), LUV (2.2%), BAH (2.1%), HON (2.0%), and GD (1.8%).

DPS Struggles to Keep Pace with Share Gains. Since 2010 for our dividend- paying coverage, there has been a 0.82 correlation between dividend per share CAGR and share price CAGR. Top performers on a share price CAGR basis from 2019 to 2024 are FTAI (54%), HWM (36%), and GE (25%), with the top dividend per share performers GE (28%), HWM (17%), and BAH (15%) (Ex 2). This compares to the top 10 current yielding names in the S&P 500, which on average have seen an - 8% share price CAGR since 2019 despite a flattish dividend per share CAGR.

Group Div Yield 60Bps Below 10Yr Average Driven by FTAI (- 5.4pts) & GE (- 1.3pts). Across our group, the average yield stands at \(1.1\%\) down from the \(1.6\%\) 10yr average. The most significant changes being with FTAI, GE, LUV, LDOS, and RTX. LUV has been the sole name with meaningful dividend yield appreciation relative to its historical average, now at \(2.2\%\) , 120bps above its average as shares have fallen at a \(3\%\) rate over the period vs DPS \(+10\%\) . Conversely, FTAI's dividend has grown at a \(10\%\) rate on \(32\%\) share gains, nearly erasing its dividend yield, now at \(0.8\%\) vs \(6.2\%\) on average. GE's yield is lagging history, as its yield of \(0.6\%\) is 130 bps below its historical yield of \(1.8\%\) on a 21pt delta between share price and DPS gains. RTX's current dividend yield of \(1.7\%\) is 70 bps below its historical average dividend yield of \(2.4\%\) , while LDOS's dividend yield of \(0.9\%\) is 80 bps below its historical average yield of \(1.7\%\) .

Dividend Yield and 10- Year Diverges Significantly. Historically, the average coverage dividend yield has typically been in the mid- \(1\%\) range with the 10- year yield roughly 1- pt higher in the mid- \(2\%\) range. Today, the 10- year yield is 3.2- pts above the average A&D dividend yield at \(4.3\%\) , while the top 10 yield in the S&P 500 are yielding \(4.6\%\) , or 3.5- pts above the A&D group. Risk- averse investors could therefore achieve a \(4\% +\) yield in T- bills compared to a relatively unattractive A&D dividend yield, although aggregate share price in a rising global demand environment for Comm'1 AM & Defense names could offer more reward for the risk undertaken.

Dividend Moves YTD. ESLT raised its quarterly dividend \(25\%\) to \(0.75 / \mathrm{sh}\) , implying a yield of \(0.6\%\) . NOC yields \(1.6\%\) today vs. defense primes at \(2.0\%\) w/ commitment to \(100\%\) FCF return to shareholders in 2025, and mgmt target of \(10\%\) CAGR to \(\) 4BB\(by 2028.

Defense & Space- BA: B- 52 Radar Modernization Program is now expected to cost \(\) 14.35\mathrm{MM}\(per tail vs original baseline of\) \ \(11.96\mathrm{MM}\) , a \(20\%\) increase, which triggered an official notice to Congress under Nunn- McCurdy. The program is part of an effort to extend the life of the B- 52 Stratofortress through keeping bombers viable with updated avionics and engines.- BA: Air Force is changing its exterior color requirements for the VC- 25B presidential airlift replacement platform, likely switching back to the administration's preferred red, white, and dark blue.- BA: Commander of Naval Air Forces Vice Adm. Daniel Cheever has confirmed that Boeing's MQ- 25 will fly by the end of 2025, with integration on naval carriers starting 2026 after repeated delays. Boeing has delivered 2 MQ- 25 aircraft for testing, with four more currently in production.- BA: State Department has approved a possible FMS sale to the United Kingdom for C- 17 Globemaster III Aircraft Sustainment Support, valued at \(\) 861\mathrm{MM}\(with Boeing named as the principal contractor.- BA: Navy awarded\) \ \(315\mathrm{MM}\) for the repair of F/A- 18 E/F aircraft landing gears.- BA/NOC: US Naval Air Forces commander Vice Adm. Daniel Cheever has indicated that the service is awaiting a down selection on the F/A- XX program. The decision had been up in the air for some time after the Pentagon's FY26 request had just \(\) 74\mathrm{MM}\$ earmarked for the program to complete the design of the aircraft as a way of "maintaining the option for F/A- XX in the future."- CACI: Awarded two contracts with the Canadian Air Force as the second phase of the Counter Uncrewed Aircraft System (C- UAS) Urgent Operational Requirement (UOR), a tactical C- UAS vehicle platform.- GE: State Department approved FMS sale to Poland for of F- 35 Sustainment and related elements of logistics and program support for an estimated cost of \(\) 1.85\mathrm{BB}\$.- General Atomics: YFQ- 42A Collaborative Combat Aircraft prototype flew for the first time on Wednesday. The flight is an important milestone toward integration of manned and unmanned fighter drone operations, with aircraft went from the build to flight test phases in just over a year. The other production- representative prototype built by Anduril (YFQ- 44A) is expected to begin flight testing soon as well.- LHX: Completed \(\) 100\mathrm{MM}\$ expansion of its satellite integration and test facility in Palm Bay to support the DoD's Golden Dome efforts.- LHX: Poland selected LHX's AN/ALQ- 254 Viper Shield electronic warfare system for its F- 16 upgrade program, which will enhance capabilities of its Block 52+ configuration on par to the new Block 70 variant offering.- LMT: In active talks with Rheinmetall for the German supplier to take over missile production in Germany, covering both ATACMS and Hellfire missiles.- NOC: Air Force's deputy chief of staff for strategic deterrence and nuclear integration, Lt. Gen. Andrew Gebara, stated that a second B- 21 bomber is likely to fly before the end of 2025. The next flight will be "an event- based process, based on the test team, the contractor and the program office," says Lt. Gen. Gebara. The first B- 21 took flight in November 2023, with the program entering LRIP soon after.- Rocket Lab: Launched 5 satellites for confidential customer, to circular orbit 413 miles above earth, w/ Electron reaching its 70th launch.- RTX: P&W awarded a potential \(\) 2.9\mathrm{BB}\$ Navy F135 Propulsion System Contract Modification to expand the production and delivery of 141 F135 propulsion systems. A modification was received in early August for \(\) 115\mathrm{MM}\$.- RTX: the State Department approved a possible FMS sale NATO Support and Procurement Agency (NSPA) of AIM- 9X Sidewinder Missiles and related equipment for an estimated cost of \(\) 103.9\mathrm{M}\$.- VOYG: Appointed Ral Tilghman as CTO. Most recently, Tilghman was chief engineer of Connected Warfare at Anduril Industries, launching a new Joint All- Domain Command and Control strategy, creating an Electromagnetic Spectrum Operations business area, new software products and fresh market opportunities. Tilghman also forged pivotal partnerships with the U.S. silicon technology base to bring new categories of defense capabilities to market.- The Air Force is asking industry to provide input about the airframe for the Next Generation Air- Refueling System as the service considers whether to pursue the program at all or simply add enhancements to the existing tanker fleet. The Army issued a request for information regarding the NGAS airframe. The parameters of its requirements are not available publicly, but an attachment listed as "controlled unclassified information" is available for select firms with access to classified material. Interested vendors have until Oct. 24 to reply.- The Pentagon's internal DOGE team is reportedly preparing a review of over 400 open contracts and grants for potential savings.- The Defense Department has told the House and Senate Armed Services committees to expects its \(\) 150\mathrm{BB}\$ reconciliation spending plan in September, missing an Aug. 22 deadline set by lawmakers, says congressional sources.

Commercial Aerospace- AIR- FP: Received the first fuselage sections from the A350F at the assembly lines in Toulouse, marking a major milestone for the program enabling the true start of assembly. The aircrafts are originally slated to enter service in 2026, but has been set back to H2:27 after repeated delays.- BA: The FAA will conduct a series of tabletop exercises with BA before considering lifting the 737 production cap. The exercises are designed to review potential issues BA may encounter as it expands beyond 38/mo.- BA: Ryanair CEO Michael O'Leary indicated he expects BA to ramp from 38/mo on the MAX to 42/mo by Oct. RYA now expects \(\sim 25\) MAX- 8200s delivered in Oct rather than Spring 2026.- BA: FAA has reportedly granted Type Inspection Authority (TIA) Phase 2D to the 777- 9, with Phase 3 to follow. Phase 2 will cover cabin systems validation, propulsion integration, redundancy and failure mode testing, and final avionics regression testing. This follows TIA Phase 2C granted in July.- BA: flew its final stored MAX (Air China) out of Moses Lake to be reactivated for delivery, the last of 450 grounded since 2019. At Q2, BA held 20 MAX- 8s for Chinese customers, w/ rework to complete and close the shadow factory in Q3.- BA/GE: Korean Air orders over 100 aircraft with GE engines, valued at \(35.6BB\) and an additional \(13.7BB\) contract with GE for engine maintenance. The deal includes 787s, 77s, 737s, and is set to largely serve as replacement aircraft.- CAE: CAE Simulation Training Private Limited (CSTPL), a joint venture between InterGlobe Enterprises and CAE, has announced the launch of a new, state- of- the- art pilot training centre in Mumbai, India. Spanning 44,000 square feet, the facility will accommodate up to six full- flight simulators (FFS) and is scheduled to begin operations in the first quarter of 2026 with two Airbus A320 FFS units. This expansion is aimed at addressing the growing demand for professional pilots in India, which is projected to reach 20,000 over the next decade.- GE: According to Magnetic Leasing and Aviation Week, the CFM56 market has reached unprecedented levels, with values for some increasing over by \(50\%\) in the past two years as it becomes increasingly complex to value engines due to varying conditions, maintenance histories, and market dynamics. Demand continues to outpace supply, especially for CFM56- 7B engines, while rising costs are prompting operators to favor shorter engine build standards over traditional long- cycle rebuilds. This shift reflects broader changes in asset strategy, driven by escalating OEM material prices and limited availability of used serviceable parts. A market correction is expected within two to three years, with smaller carriers most at risk.- RTX: Aircraft wheel production time reduced from 45 to 7 days by consolidating legacy equipment and streamlining workflows.- RTX: Collins providing JBLU with FlightAware Foresight technology, a predictive analytics took for improving visibility, efficiency, decision- making for airlines.

Airlines- AAPA: Association of Asia Pacific Airlines (AAPA) registered a \(7.7\%\) y- o- y increase in international passengers carried (33.4MM total), w/ RPKs \(+8.0\%\) on ASKs \(+8.6\%\) bringing LF down 0.4pts to \(82.0\%\) - DAL: Will resume TLV service from JFK on Sept 1 with its A330- 900neo. UAL resumed service on July 21st, now w/ 2x daily.- DAL/LUV: In June, DAL set the expectation to grow connectivity in Austin by \(50\%\) to 120 daily departures and 29 destinations (from 25), threatening LUV's \(40\% +\) departure share at AUS. DAL will open a cabin crew base in Austin in Q4:25. LUV has since stated it wants to be the anchor tenant at AUS w/ 18 gates (from 10), creating capacity to grow daily flights by \(>50\%\) to over 200 (from 130/daily), on pace to become the largest LUV service in Texas.- JBLU: JBLU and Germany's Condor expanding the partnership to allow TrueBlue earn & burn for flights operated by Condor.- LUV: partnered with EVA Air to jointly operate itineraries from LAX, SFO, SEA, and ORD to Asia. This is LUV's 3rd int'l partner (and 2nd to Taiwan) along w/ Icelandair and China Airlines.- ULCC: Adding 20 new routes in November through February from Detroit, Houston, Baltimore, Fort Lauderdale, Charlotte, and Dallas w/ fares starting at \(29 for tickets purchased through Sept 1. 19 of 20 routes overlap with Spirit.- ULCC: Frontier- Barclays Mastercard will now offer companion certificates on top of existing reward until Jan 31st, 2026, w/ the 1st at\) 3K in purchases, 2nd at \(10K,\) and 3rd at \(20K. ULCC is also offering miles match up to 1MM miles from qualifying airlines, based on earning that same balance over 12 mos. ULCC is also extending the Frontier Elite Gold Status upgrade for\) 69 from LUV, JBLU, Spirit, and ALK loyalty programs.- RYA: CEO O'Leary stated bookings remain strong, and its financial guidance last issued in mid- August is unchanged. Ryanair continues to expect to recover most, but not all the \(7\%\) decline in fares in the year ago period. \(70\%\) of Sept seats are sold, with the remaining close- in bookings important to the quarter's results.

- RYA: signed a partnership with Booking Holdings to make it an Approved OTA, allowing for full price transparency & allowing access to myRyanair accounts w/o add'l verification. This concludes all open litigation, which was originally brought forth by Ryanair in 2020 for ticket scraping & added charges by OTAs to fares.- Spirit (FLYY): transferred an add'l \(\) 50\$ MM to its credit card processor and will allow holdbacks of \(\) 3\$ MM/day until fully collateralized in order to extend the term of the processing agreement from Dec 31, 2025 to Dec 31, 2027. Spirit has set aside about \(\) 300\$ MM as collateral (versus max exposure up to \(\sim\) \(\) 500\$ MM), including \(\) 200\$ MM in a deposit account, \(\) 50\$ MM in a restricted account, and the latest \(\) 50\$ MM.

Buy - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of \(15\%\) or more within a 12- month period. Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus \(15\%\) or minus \(10\%\) within a 12- month period. Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period. The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) is \(20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus \(20\%\) within a 12- month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus \(20\%\) or less within a 12- month period. NR - The investment rating and price target have been temporarily suspended. Such suspensions are in compliance with applicable regulations and/or Jefferies policies.

NC - Not covered. Jefferies does not cover this company.

Restricted - Describes issuers where, in conjunction with Jefferies engagement in certain transactions, company policy or applicable securities regulations prohibit certain types of communications, including investment recommendations.
